Judges’ stories are as sensational as today’s tabloids: gruesome murders, sexual depravity, superhuman feats of strength, a bizarre mutilation. But beneath the sensational stories are eternal lessons you’ll never find in a tabloid. The book of Judges shows what can happen when a society slides into moral anarchy. It also shows how God displays his mercy when people cry out to him in repentance.

Judges describes the Israelites’ life in Canaan after the death of Joshua and before the time of the kings. In chapters 1-16, you will read a recurring tale that recounts how the Israelites related to God and the impact it had on their national destiny. Each story:
• begins by telling of God’s blessing;
• then speaks of how the Israelites fell into wayward idolatry;
• which resulted in them being conquered by their enemies and suffering greatly.
• In the midst of their anguish they would return to God in repentance;
• and then experience God’s merciful deliverance through one of the judges.

This sequence of events repeats itself in various ways six times in this book! The result is a series of poignant stories that are both heart-wrenching and heartwarming. They speak of God’s abiding faithfulness and unrelenting love toward his wandering people. By the end of this book, you long for the intervention of yet another judge who will come to save—a longing that will only be fulfilled with Jesus’ advent.

As you study the book of Judges, you may want to examine your own life and identify areas where you have been disobedient. Then ask God to forgive you and to deliver you from the consequences that have occurred as a result of having strayed from a passionate pursuit of relationship with God.

In the two books of Samuel, the words of God (the red sections) are few but pivotal. In 1 Samuel God speaks 22 times, in 2 Samuel he speaks ten times. Note to whom he speaks in each book.

In 1 Samuel God speaks to:
• Eli once (God 1);
• Samuel fifteen times (God 2,3,4,5,6,7,8,9,10,12,13,14,15,16,17);
• The Israelite leaders once (God 11);
• David five times (God 18,19,20,21,22).

In 2 Samuel God speaks to:
  David seven times (God 1,2,3,4,5,7,8);
• Nathan once (God 6);
• Gad once (God 9);
• The death angel once (God 10).

“Clearly, in 1 Samuel the main recipient of God’s communication is Samuel himself: to him God speaks 356 (50.3 percent) of the 708 red words in this book. Of special note are the final two times God speaks to the prophet. In God 16, God reveals to Samuel an important principle: “The Lord doesn’t see things the way you see them. People judge by outward appearance, but the Lord looks at the heart.” This principle is echoed several times in the scriptures most importantly by Jesus himself in the gospel of Luke Jesus 124. God’s final word to Samuel marks a key transition. In God 17 he gives Samuel this instruction concerning David: "This is the one; anoint him." From that moment on, there is no record of God speaking to Samuel, and—in the remainder of this book and the next—God speaks to David twelve times.

Though God speaks directly to David more frequently than to anyone else in 2 Samuel, his longest message is to the prophet Nathan for David. This prophetic encouragement comprises nearly three-fourths of God’s communication in the whole book! It affirms God’s incredible mercy to David when he repents before God for his adultery with Bathsheba and for having her husband Uriah killed. God’s faithful love for those who fully acknowledge their sin and turn back to him is central to the story of 1 & 2 Samuel. Do we really get this? If God could speak in this way to an adulterer and murderer, how then would he speak to us when we who are sinners turn back to him? As you read these books, ponder on his mercy and ask God to reveal the breadth and depth of his compassion and forgiveness towards you.

There are two lead actors in Acts: Peter and Paul. Peter speaks a total of 36 times (2,376 words)—31 times alone and 5 times together with others. Paul speaks a total of 56 times (3,708 words)—53 times alone and 3 times together with others. The words of these two fill more than one-fourth of the text of Acts (Peter 10 percent and Paul 16 percent).

“Read and reflect on the three longest speeches of each of these two lead actors, noting the similarities and differences between them. Peter’s main speeches are:
• “His message in the temple of Jerusalem on the day of Pentecost (Simon Peter 3-5);
• His message in the temple of Jerusalem after healing a man lame from birth (Simon Peter 8-9);
• His testimony to the believers in Jerusalem after meeting with Cornelius (Simon Peter 24-25).

Paul’s main speeches are:
• His message in the synagogue of Antioch of Pisidia on the first missionary journey (Paul 4-5);
• His testimony in the temple of Jerusalem at the time of his arrest (Paul 28-30);
• His testimony in Caesarea before Herod Agrippa and Governor Porcius Festus (Paul 45).

“In addition to Peter and Paul, there are an additional 61 speaking parts in Acts including individuals and groups, human, demonic, and angelic. These blue sections of Acts occupy 30 percent of the book. The three longest blue speeches are:
• Stephen’s message in Jerusalem when on trial before the Jewish high council (Stephen 1);
• Festus’ explanation to Herod Agrippa about Paul’s case (Governor Porcius Festus 4-5);
• James’s decision at the conclusion of the council of Jerusalem (James the Brother of Jesus 1)
